# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: remote-attestation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:remote-attestation/attestation] An **attestation** is something that serves to bear witness, confirm, authenticate or verify the validity of some fact or status.
[src:remote-attestation/attestation] An *attestor* is someone who performs an attestation.
[src:remote-attestation/attestation] An *attestation date* is the date on which an attestation is performed.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] In principle the privacy issue could be resolved using any standard signature scheme (or public key encryption) and a single key pair.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] Manufacturers would embed the private key into every TPM produced and the public key would be published as a certificate.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] Signatures produced by the TPM must have originated from the private key, by the nature of the technology, and since all TPMs use the same private key they are indistinguishable ensuring the user's privacy.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] This rather naive solution relies upon the assumption that there exists a *global secret*.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] One only needs to look at the precedent of Content Scramble System (CSS), an encryption system for DVDs, to see that this assumption is fundamentally flawed.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] Furthermore, this approach fails to realize a secondary goal: the ability to detect rogue TPMs.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] A rogue TPM is a TPM that has been compromised and had its secrets extracted.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] The solution first adopted by the TCG (TPM specification v1.1) required a trusted third-party, namely a *privacy certificate authority* (privacy CA).
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] Each TPM has an embedded RSA key pair called an Endorsement Key (EK) which the privacy CA is assumed to know.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] In order to attest the TPM generates a second RSA key pair called an Attestation Identity Key (AIK).
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] It sends the public AIK, signed by EK, to the privacy CA who checks its validity and issues a certificate for the AIK.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] (For this to work, either a) the privacy CA must know the TPM's public EK *a priori*, or b) the TPM's manufacturer must have provided an *endorsement certificate*.) The host/TPM is now able to authenticate itself with respect to the certificate.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] The number of permitted requests should be subject to a risk management exercise.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] This solution is problematic since the privacy CA must take part in every transaction and thus must provide high availability whilst remaining secure.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] Furthermore, privacy requirements may be violated if the privacy CA and verifier collude.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] Although the latter issue can probably be resolved using blind signatures, the first remains.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] The EPID 2.0 solution embeds the private key in the microprocessor when it is manufactured, inherently distributes the key with the physical device shipment, and has the key provisioned and ready for use with 1st power-on.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] The DAA protocol is based on three entities and two different steps.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] The entities are the DAA Member (TPM platform or EPID-enabled microprocessor), the DAA Issuer and the DAA Verifier.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] The issuer is charged to verify the TPM platform during the Join step and to issue DAA credential to the platform.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] The platform (Member) uses the DAA credential with the Verifier during the Sign step.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] Through a zero-knowledge proof the Verifier can verify the credential without attempting to violate the platform's privacy.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] The protocol also supports a blocklisting capability so that Verifiers can identify attestations from TPMs that have been compromised.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] The protocol allows differing degrees of privacy.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] Interactions are always anonymous, but the Member/Verifier may negotiate as to whether the Verifier is able to link transactions.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] This would allow user profiling and/or the rejection of requests originating from a host which has made too many requests.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] The Member and Verifier can also elect to reveal additional information to accomplish non-anonymous interactions (just as you can choose to tell a stranger your full name, or not).
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] Thus, known identity can be built on top of an anonymous start.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] The first Direct Anonymous Attestation scheme was due to Brickell, Camenisch, and Chen; that scheme proved insecure and required a fix.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] Brickell, Chen, and Li improved efficiency of that first scheme using symmetric pairings, rather than RSA.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] And Chen, Morrissey, and Smart attempted to further improve efficiency by switching from a symmetric to an asymmetric setting; unfortunately, the asymmetric scheme was also insecure.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] Chen, Page, and Smart proposed a new elliptic curve cryptography scheme using Barreto–Naehrig curves.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] This scheme is implemented by both EPID 2.0 and the TPM 2.0 standard.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] It is recommended for TPMs in general and required for TPMs that conform to the PC client profile.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] In addition, the Intel EPID 2.0 implementation of ISO/IEC 20008 DAA and the available open source SDK can be used for members and verifiers to do attestation.
[src:remote-attestation/direct-anonymous-attestation] Since one of the DAA attestation methods in TPM 2.0 is identical to EPID 2.0, work is underway to make ISO/IEC 20008 DAA and TPM 2.0 DAA attestation read consistently with each other at the spec level.
[src:remote-attestation/root-of-trust] In cryptographic systems with hierarchical structure, a **trust anchor** is an authoritative entity for which trust is assumed and not derived.
[src:remote-attestation/root-of-trust] In the X.509 architecture, a root certificate would be the trust anchor from which the whole chain of trust is derived.
[src:remote-attestation/root-of-trust] The trust anchor must be in the possession of the trusting party beforehand to make any further certificate path validation possible.
[src:remote-attestation/root-of-trust] Most operating systems provide a built-in list of self-signed root certificates to act as trust anchors for applications.
[src:remote-attestation/root-of-trust] The Firefox web browser also provides its own list of trust anchors.
[src:remote-attestation/root-of-trust] The end-user of an operating system or web browser is implicitly trusting in the correct operation of that software, and the software manufacturer in turn is delegating trust for certain cryptographic operations to the certificate authorities responsible for the root certificates.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing-group] The **Trusted Computing Group** is a group formed in 2003 as the successor to the Trusted Computing Platform Alliance which was previously formed in 1999 to implement Trusted Computing concepts across personal computers.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing-group] Members include Intel, AMD, IBM, Microsoft, and Cisco.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing-group] The core idea of trusted computing is to give hardware manufacturers control over what software does and does not run on a system by refusing to run unsigned software.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing-group] On October 11, 1999, the Trusted Computing Platform Alliance (abbreviated as TCPA), a consortium of various technology companies including Compaq, Hewlett-Packard, IBM, Intel, and Microsoft, was formed in an effort to promote trust and security in the personal computing platform.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing-group] In November 1999, the TCPA announced that over 70 leading hardware and software companies joined the alliance in the first month.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing-group] On January 30, 2001, version 1.0 of the Trusted Computing Platform Specifications was released.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing-group] IBM was the first original equipment manufacturer to incorporate hardware features based on the specifications with the introduction of its ThinkPad T30 mobile computer in 2002.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing-group] In 2003, the TCPA was succeeded by the Trusted Computing Group, with an increased emphasis on mobile devices.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing-group] Promoters pay annual membership fees of $30,000, contributors pay $15,000, and depending upon company size, adopters pay annual membership fees of either $2,500 or $7,500.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing-group] TCG's most successful effort was the development of a Trusted Platform Module (TPM), a semiconductor intellectual property core or integrated circuit that conforms to the specification to enable trusted computing features in computers and mobile devices.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing-group] Related efforts involved Trusted Network Connect, to bring trusted computing to network connections, and Storage Core Architecture / Security Subsystem Class, to bring trusted computing to disk drives and other storage devices.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing-group] These efforts have not achieved the same level of widespread adoption as the trusted platform module.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing-group] The group historically faced opposition from the free software community on the grounds that the technology had a negative impact on the users' privacy and can create customer lock-in, especially if it is used to create DRM applications.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing-group] It received criticism from the Linux and FreeBSD communities, as well as the software development community in general.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Trusted Computing proponents such as International Data Corporation, the Enterprise Strategy Group and Endpoint Technologies Associates state that the technology will make computers safer, less prone to viruses and malware, and thus more reliable from an end-user perspective.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] They also state that Trusted Computing will allow computers and servers to offer improved computer security over that which is currently available.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Opponents often state that this technology will be used primarily to enforce digital rights management policies (imposed restrictions to the owner) and not to increase computer security.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Chip manufacturers Intel and AMD, hardware manufacturers such as HP and Dell, and operating system providers such as Microsoft include Trusted Computing in their products if enabled.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Army requires that every new PC it purchases comes with a Trusted Platform Module (TPM).
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] As of July 3, 2007, so does virtually the entire United States Department of Defense.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The endorsement key is a 2048-bit RSA public and private key pair that is created randomly on the chip at manufacture time and cannot be changed.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The private key never leaves the chip, while the public key is used for attestation and for encryption of sensitive data sent to the chip, as occurs during the TPM_TakeOwnership command.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The TPM should be designed to make the extraction of this key by hardware analysis hard, but tamper resistance is not a strong requirement.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Memory curtaining extends common memory protection techniques to provide full isolation of sensitive areas of memory—for example, locations containing cryptographic keys.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Even the operating system does not have full access to curtained memory.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The exact implementation details are vendor specific.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Sealed storage protects private information by binding it to platform configuration information including the software and hardware being used.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] This means the data can be released only to a particular combination of software and hardware.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Sealed storage can be used for DRM enforcing.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] For example, users who keep a song on their computer that has not been licensed to be listened will not be able to play it.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Currently, a user can locate the song, listen to it, and send it to someone else, play it in the software of their choice, or back it up (and in some cases, use circumvention software to decrypt it).
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Alternatively, the user may use software to modify the operating system's DRM routines to have it leak the song data once, say, a temporary license was acquired.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Using sealed storage, the song is securely encrypted using a key bound to the trusted platform module so that only the unmodified and untampered music player on his or her computer can play it.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] In this DRM architecture, this might also prevent people from listening to the song after buying a new computer, or upgrading parts of their current one, except after explicit permission of the vendor of the song.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Remote attestation allows changes to the user's computer to be detected by authorized parties.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] For example, software companies can identify unauthorized changes to software, including users modifying their software to circumvent commercial digital rights restrictions.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] It works by having the hardware generate a certificate stating what software is currently running.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The computer can then present this certificate to a remote party to show that unaltered software is currently executing.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Numerous remote attestation schemes have been proposed for various computer architectures, including Intel, RISC-V, and ARM.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Remote attestation is usually combined with public-key encryption so that the information sent can only be read by the programs that requested the attestation, and not by an eavesdropper.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] To take the song example again, the user's music player software could send the song to other machines, but only if they could attest that they were running an authorized copy of the music player software.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] To preserve the privacy of attestation responders, Direct Anonymous Attestation has been proposed as a solution, which uses a group signature scheme to prevent revealing the identity of individual signers.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Proof of space (PoS) have been proposed to be used for malware detection, by determining whether the L1 cache of a processor is empty (e.g., has enough space to evaluate the PoSpace routine without cache misses) or contains a routine that resisted being evicted.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The Microsoft products Windows Vista, Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows RT make use of a Trusted Platform Module to facilitate BitLocker Drive Encryption.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Other known applications with runtime encryption and the use of secure enclaves include the Signal messenger and the e-prescription service ("E-Rezept") by the German government.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Trusted Computing would allow companies to create a digital rights management (DRM) system which would be very hard to circumvent, though not impossible.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Sealed storage could be used to prevent the user from opening the file with an unauthorized player or computer.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Remote attestation could be used to authorize play only by music players that enforce the record company's rules.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The music would be played from curtained memory, which would prevent the user from making an unrestricted copy of the file while it is playing, and secure I/O would prevent capturing what is being sent to the sound system.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Circumventing such a system would require either manipulation of the computer's hardware, capturing the analogue (and thus degraded) signal using a recording device or a microphone, or breaking the security of the system.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] New business models for use of software (services) over Internet may be boosted by the technology.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] By strengthening the DRM system, one could base a business model on renting programs for a specific time periods or "pay as you go" models.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] For instance, one could download a music file which could only be played a certain number of times before it becomes unusable, or the music file could be used only within a certain time period.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Trusted Computing could be used to combat cheating in online games.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Some players modify their game copy in order to gain unfair advantages in the game; remote attestation, secure I/O and memory curtaining could be used to determine that all players connected to a server were running an unmodified copy of the software.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Trusted Computing could be used to guarantee participants in a grid computing system are returning the results of the computations they claim to be instead of forging them.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] This would allow large scale simulations to be run (say a climate simulation) without expensive redundant computations to guarantee malicious hosts are not undermining the results to achieve the conclusion they want.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The Electronic Frontier Foundation and the Free Software Foundation criticize that trust in the underlying companies is not deserved and that the technology puts too much power and control into the hands of those who design systems and software.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] They also state that it may cause consumers to lose anonymity in their online interactions, as well as mandating technologies Trusted Computing opponents say are unnecessary.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] They suggest Trusted Computing as a possible enabler for future versions of mandatory access control, copy protection, and DRM.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Some security experts, such as Alan Cox and Bruce Schneier, have spoken out against Trusted Computing, believing it will provide computer manufacturers and software authors with increased control to impose restrictions on what users are able to do with their computers.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] There are concerns that Trusted Computing would have an anti-competitive effect on the IT market.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] There is concern amongst critics that it will not always be possible to examine the hardware components on which Trusted Computing relies, the Trusted Platform Module, which is the ultimate hardware system where the core 'root' of trust in the platform has to reside.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] If not implemented correctly, it presents a security risk to overall platform integrity and protected data.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The specifications, as published by the Trusted Computing Group, are open and are available for anyone to review.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] However, the final implementations by commercial vendors will not necessarily be subjected to the same review process.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] In addition, the world of cryptography can often move quickly, and that hardware implementations of algorithms might create an inadvertent obsolescence.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Trusting networked computers to controlling authorities rather than to individuals may create digital imprimaturs.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] One of the early motivations behind trusted computing was a desire by media and software corporations for stricter DRM technology to prevent users from freely sharing and using potentially copyrighted or private files without explicit permission.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] An example could be downloading a music file from a band: the band's record company could come up with rules for how the band's music can be used.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] For example, they might want the user to play the file only three times a day without paying additional money.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Also, they could use remote attestation to only send their music to a music player that enforces their rules: sealed storage would prevent the user from opening the file with another player that did not enforce the restrictions.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Memory curtaining would prevent the user from making an unrestricted copy of the file while it is playing, and secure output would prevent capturing what is sent to the sound system.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] A user who wanted to switch to a competing program might find that it would be impossible for that new program to read old data, as the information would be "locked in" to the old program.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] It could also make it impossible for the user to read or modify their data except as specifically permitted by the software.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The law in many countries allows users certain rights over data whose copyright they do not own (including text, images, and other media), often under headings such as fair use or public interest.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Depending on jurisdiction, these may cover issues such as whistleblowing, production of evidence in court, quoting or other small-scale usage, backups of owned media, and making a copy of owned material for personal use on other owned devices or systems.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The steps implicit in trusted computing have the practical effect of preventing users exercising these legal rights.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] A service that requires external validation or permission - such as a music file or game that requires connection with the vendor to confirm permission to play or use - is vulnerable to that service being withdrawn or no longer updated.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] A number of incidents have already occurred where users, having purchased music or video media, have found their ability to watch or listen to it suddenly stop due to vendor policy or cessation of service, or server inaccessibility, at times with no compensation.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Alternatively in some cases the vendor refuses to provide services in future which leaves purchased material only usable on the present -and increasingly obsolete- hardware (so long as it lasts) but not on any hardware that may be purchased in future.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Some opponents of Trusted Computing advocate "owner override": allowing an owner who is confirmed to be physically present to allow the computer to bypass restrictions and use the secure I/O path.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Such an override would allow remote attestation to a user's specification, e.g., to create certificates that say Internet Explorer is running, even if a different browser is used.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Instead of preventing software change, remote attestation would indicate when the software has been changed without owner's permission.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Trusted Computing Group members have refused to implement owner override.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Proponents of trusted computing believe that owner override defeats the trust in other computers since remote attestation can be forged by the owner.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Owner override offers the security and enforcement benefits to a machine owner, but does not allow them to trust other computers, because their owners could waive rules or restrictions on their own computers.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Under this scenario, once data is sent to someone else's computer, whether it be a diary, a DRM music file, or a joint project, that other person controls what security, if any, their computer will enforce on their copy of those data.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] This has the potential to undermine the applications of trusted computing to enforce DRM, control cheating in online games and attest to remote computations for grid computing.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Because a Trusted Computing equipped computer is able to uniquely attest to its own identity, it will be possible for vendors and others who possess the ability to use the attestation feature to zero in on the identity of the user of TC-enabled software with a high degree of certainty.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Such a capability is contingent on the reasonable chance that the user at some time provides user-identifying information, whether voluntarily, indirectly, or simply through inference of many seemingly benign pieces of data.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] (e.g. search records, as shown through simple study of the AOL search records leak).
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] One common way that information can be obtained and linked is when a user registers a computer just after purchase.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Another common way is when a user provides identifying information to the website of an affiliate of the vendor.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] While proponents of TC point out that online purchases and credit transactions could potentially be more secure as a result of the remote attestation capability, this may cause the computer user to lose expectations of anonymity when using the Internet.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Critics point out that this could have a chilling effect on political free speech, the ability of journalists to use anonymous sources, whistle blowing, political blogging and other areas where the public needs protection from retaliation through anonymity.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The TPM specification offers features and suggested implementations that are meant to address the anonymity requirement.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] By using a third-party Privacy Certification Authority (PCA), the information that identifies the computer could be held by a trusted third party.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Additionally, the use of direct anonymous attestation (DAA), introduced in TPM v1.2, allows a client to perform attestation while not revealing any personally identifiable or machine information.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The kind of data that must be supplied to the TTP in order to get the trusted status is at present not entirely clear, but the TCG itself admits that "attestation is an important TPM function with significant privacy implications".
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] It is, however, clear that both static and dynamic information about the user computer may be supplied (Ekpubkey) to the TTP (v1.1b), it is not clear what data will be supplied to the “verifier” under v1.2.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The static information will uniquely identify the endorser of the platform, model, details of the TPM, and that the platform (PC) complies with the TCG specifications .
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The dynamic information is described as software running on the computer.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] If a program like Windows is registered in the user's name this in turn will uniquely identify the user.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Another dimension of privacy infringing capabilities might also be introduced with this new technology; how often you use your programs might be possible information provided to the TTP.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] In an exceptional, however practical situation, where a user purchases a pornographic movie on the Internet, the purchaser nowadays, must accept the fact that he has to provide credit card details to the provider, thereby possibly risking being identified.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] With the new technology a purchaser might also risk someone finding out that he (or she) has watched this pornographic movie 1000 times.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] This adds a new dimension to the possible privacy infringement.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The extent of data that will be supplied to the TTP/Verifiers is at present not exactly known, only when the technology is implemented and used will we be able to assess the exact nature and volume of the data that is transmitted.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Trusted Computing requests that all software and hardware vendors will follow the technical specifications released by the Trusted Computing Group in order to allow interoperability between different trusted software stacks.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] However, since at least mid-2006, there have been interoperability problems between the TrouSerS trusted software stack (released as open source software by IBM) and Hewlett-Packard's stack.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Another problem is that the technical specifications are still changing, so it is unclear which is the standard implementation of the trusted stack.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] People have voiced concerns that trusted computing could be used to keep or discourage users from running software created by companies outside of a small industry group.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The concerns about trusted computing being used to shut out competition exist within a broader framework of consumers being concerned about using bundling of products to obscure prices of products and to engage in anti-competitive practices.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Trusted Computing is seen as harmful or problematic to independent and open source software developers.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] In the widely used public-key cryptography, creation of keys can be done on the local computer and the creator has complete control over who has access to it, and consequentially their own security policies.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] In some proposed encryption-decryption chips, a private/public key is permanently embedded into the hardware when it is manufactured, and hardware manufacturers would have the opportunity to record the key without leaving evidence of doing so.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] With this key it would be possible to have access to data encrypted with it, and to authenticate as it.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] It is trivial for a manufacturer to give a copy of this key to the government or the software manufacturers, as the platform must go through steps so that it works with authenticated software.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] A security breach breaking that chain of trust happened to a SIM card manufacturer Gemalto, which in 2010 was infiltrated by US and British spies, resulting in compromised security of cellphone calls.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] It is also critical that one be able to trust that the hardware manufacturers and software developers properly implement trusted computing standards.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Incorrect implementation could be hidden from users, and thus could undermine the integrity of the whole system without users being aware of the flaw.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Since 2004, most major manufacturers have shipped systems that have included Trusted Platform Modules, with associated BIOS support.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] In accordance with the TCG specifications, the user must enable the Trusted Platform Module before it can be used.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Processor manufacturers have included secure enclaves in their design such as ARM TrustZone, Intel Management Engine with SGX and AMD PSP with Secure Encrypted Virtualization.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The Linux kernel has included trusted computing support since version 2.6.13, and there are several projects to implement trusted computing for Linux.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] In January 2005, members of Gentoo Linux's "crypto herd" announced their intention of providing support for TC—in particular support for the Trusted Platform Module.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] There is also a TCG-compliant software stack for Linux named TrouSerS, released under an open source license.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] There are several open-source projects that facilitate the use of confidential computing technology, including EGo, EdgelessDB and MarbleRun from Edgeless Systems, as well as Enarx, which originates from security research at Red Hat.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Some limited form of trusted computing can be implemented on current versions of Microsoft Windows with third-party software.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Major cloud providers such as Microsoft Azure, AWS and Google Cloud Platform have virtual machines with trusted computing features available.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] The Intel Classmate PC (a competitor to the One Laptop Per Child) includes a Trusted Platform Module.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] PrivateCore vCage software can be used to attest x86 servers with TPM chips.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Google enforces Play Integrity API to Android devices with their bootloader unlocked.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Mobile T6 secure operating system simulates the TPM functionality in mobile devices using the ARM TrustZone technology.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-computing] Samsung smartphones come equipped with Samsung Knox that depend on features like Secure Boot, TIMA, MDM, TrustZone and SE Linux.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] A **Trusted Platform Module** (**TPM**) is a secure cryptoprocessor that implements the **ISO/IEC 11889** standard.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Common uses are verifying that the boot process starts from a trusted combination of hardware and software and storing disk encryption keys.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] A TPM 2.0 implementation is part of the Windows 11 system requirements.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The first TPM version that was deployed was 1.1b in 2003.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Trusted Platform Module (TPM) was conceived by a computer industry consortium called Trusted Computing Group (TCG).
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] It evolved into *TPM Main Specification Version 1.2* which was standardized by International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in 2009 as ISO/IEC 11889:2009.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] *TPM Main Specification Version 1.2* was finalized on 3 March 2011 completing its revision.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] On April 9, 2014, the Trusted Computing Group announced a major upgrade to their specification entitled *TPM Library Specification 2.0*.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The group continues work on the standard incorporating errata, algorithmic additions and new commands, with its most recent edition published as 2.0 in November 2019.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] When a new revision is released, it is divided into multiple parts by the Trusted Computing Group.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Each part consists of a document that makes up the whole of the new TPM specification.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] While TPM 2.0 addresses many of the same use cases and has similar features, the details are different.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] TPM 2.0 is not backward compatible with TPM 1.2.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The TPM 2.0 policy authorization includes the 1.2 HMAC, locality, physical presence, and PCR.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] It adds authorization based on an asymmetric digital signature, indirection to another authorization secret, counters and time limits, NVRAM values, a particular command or command parameters, and physical presence.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] It permits the ANDing and ORing of these authorization primitives to construct complex authorization policies.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Computer programs can use a TPM for the authentication of hardware devices, since each TPM chip has a unique and secret Endorsement Key (EK) burned in as it is produced.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Security embedded in hardware provides more protection than a software-only solution.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Its use is restricted in some countries.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The primary scope of TPM is to ensure the integrity of a platform during boot time.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] In this context, "integrity" means "behaves as intended", and a "platform" is any computer device regardless of its operating system.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] This is to ensure that the boot process starts from a trusted combination of hardware and software, and continues until the operating system has fully booted and applications are running.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] When TPM is used, the firmware and the operating system are responsible for ensuring integrity.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] For example, the Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) can use TPM to form a root of trust: The TPM contains several Platform Configuration Registers (PCRs) that allow secure storage and reporting of security-relevant metrics.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] These metrics can be used to detect changes to previous configurations and decide how to proceed.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Examples of such use can be found in Linux Unified Key Setup (LUKS), BitLocker and PrivateCore vCage memory encryption.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Another example of platform integrity via TPM is in the use of Microsoft Office 365 licensing and Outlook Exchange.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Another example of TPM use for platform integrity is the Trusted Execution Technology (TXT), which creates a chain of trust.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] It could remotely attest that a computer is using the specified hardware and software.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Full disk encryption utilities, such as dm-crypt, can use this technology to protect the keys used to encrypt the computer's storage devices and provide integrity authentication for a trusted boot pathway that includes firmware and the boot sector.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] In 2006, new laptops began being sold with a built-in TPM chip.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] In the future, this concept could be co-located on an existing motherboard chip in computers, or any other device where the TPM facilities could be employed, such as a cellphone.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] On a PC, either the Low Pin Count (LPC) bus or the Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI) bus is used to connect to the TPM chip.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The official TCG reference implementation of the TPM 2.0 Specification has been developed by Microsoft.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] It is licensed under BSD License and the source code is available on GitHub.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] In 2018, Intel open-sourced its Trusted Platform Module 2.0 (TPM2) software stack with support for Linux and Microsoft Windows.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The source code is hosted on GitHub and licensed under BSD License.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Infineon funded the development of an open source TPM middleware that complies with the Software Stack (TSS) Enhanced System API (ESAPI) specification of the TCG.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] It was developed by Fraunhofer Institute for Secure Information Technology (SIT).
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] IBM's Software TPM 2.0 is an implementation of the TCG TPM 2.0 specification.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] It is based on the TPM specification Parts 3 and 4 and source code donated by Microsoft.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] It contains additional files to complete the implementation.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The source code is hosted on SourceForge and GitHub and licensed under BSD License.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] In 2022, AMD announced that under certain circumstances their fTPM implementation causes performance problems.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] A fix is available in form of a BIOS-Update.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The Trusted Computing Group (TCG) has faced resistance to the deployment of this technology in some areas, where some authors see possible uses not specifically related to Trusted Computing, which may raise privacy concerns.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The concerns include the abuse of remote validation of software to decide what software is allowed to run, and possible ways to follow actions taken by the user and record them in a database in a manner that is completely undetectable to the user.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The TrueCrypt disk encryption utility, as well as its derivative VeraCrypt, do not support TPM.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The original TrueCrypt developers were of the opinion that the exclusive purpose of the TPM is "to protect against attacks that require the attacker to have administrator privileges, or physical access to the computer".
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The attacker who has physical or administrative access to a computer can circumvent TPM, e.g., by installing a hardware keystroke logger, by resetting TPM, or by capturing memory contents and retrieving TPM-issued keys.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The condemning text goes so far as to claim that TPM is entirely redundant.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The VeraCrypt publisher has reproduced the original allegation with no changes other than replacing "TrueCrypt" with "VeraCrypt".
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The author is right that, after achieving either unrestricted physical access or administrative privileges, it is only a matter of time before other security measures in place are bypassed.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] However, stopping an attacker in possession of administrative privileges has never been one of the goals of TPM (see § Uses for details), and TPM can stop some physical tampering.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] In 2015, Richard Stallman suggested replacing the term "trusted computing" with the term "treacherous computing" due to the danger that the computer can be made to systematically disobey its owner if the cryptographical keys are kept secret from them.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] In August 2023, Linus Torvalds, who was frustrated with AMD fTPM's stuttering bugs, opined, "Let's just disable the stupid fTPM `hwrnd` thing." He said the CPU-based random number generation, `rdrand`, was equally suitable, despite having its share of bugs.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] In 2010, Christopher Tarnovsky presented an attack against TPMs at Black Hat Briefings, where he claimed to be able to extract secrets from a single TPM.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] He was able to do this after 6 months of work by inserting a probe and spying on an internal bus for the Infineon SLE 66 CL PC.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] In case of physical access, computers with TPM 1.2 are vulnerable to cold boot attacks as long as the system is on or can be booted without a passphrase from shutdown, sleep or hibernation, which is the default setup for Windows computers with BitLocker full disk encryption.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] A fix was proposed, which has been adopted in the specifications for TPM 2.0.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] In 2009, the concept of shared authorisation data in TPM 1.2 was found to be flawed.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] An adversary given access to the data could spoof responses from the TPM.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] In 2015, as part of the Snowden revelations, it was revealed that in 2010 a US CIA team claimed at an internal conference to have carried out a differential power analysis attack against TPMs that was able to extract secrets.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Main Trusted Boot (tboot) distributions before November 2017 are affected by a dynamic root of trust for measurement (DRTM) attack CVE-2017-16837, which affects computers running on Intel's Trusted eXecution Technology (TXT) for the boot-up routine.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] In October 2017, it was reported that a code library developed by Infineon, which had been in widespread use in its TPMs, contained a vulnerability, known as ROCA, which generated weak RSA key pairs that allowed private keys to be inferred from public keys.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] As a result, all systems depending upon the privacy of such weak keys are vulnerable to compromise, such as identity theft or spoofing.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Cryptosystems that store encryption keys directly in the TPM without blinding could be at particular risk to these types of attacks, as passwords and other factors would be meaningless if the attacks can extract encryption secrets.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Infineon has released firmware updates for its TPMs to manufacturers who have used them.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] In 2018, a design flaw in the TPM 2.0 specification for the static root of trust for measurement (SRTM) was reported (CVE-2018-6622).
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] It allows an adversary to reset and forge platform configuration registers which are designed to securely hold measurements of software that are used for bootstrapping a computer.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Fixing it requires hardware-specific firmware patches.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] An attacker abuses power interrupts and TPM state restores to trick TPM into thinking that it is running on non-tampered components.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] In 2021, the Dolos Group showed an attack on a discrete TPM, where the TPM chip itself had some tamper resistance, but the other endpoints of its communication bus did not.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] They read a full-disk-encryption key as it was transmitted across the motherboard, and used it to decrypt the laptop's SSD.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] As of 2025, a TPM is provided by nearly all PC and notebook manufacturers in their products.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] There are also hybrid types; for example, TPM can be integrated into an Ethernet controller, thus eliminating the need for a separate motherboard component.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Field upgrade is the TCG term for updating the TPM firmware.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The update can be between TPM 1.2 and TPM 2.0, or between firmware versions.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Some vendors limit the number of transitions between 1.2 and 2.0, and some restrict rollback to previous versions.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Platform OEMs such as HP supply an upgrade tool.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Since July 28, 2016, all new Microsoft device models, lines, or series (or updating the hardware configuration of an existing model, line, or series with a major update, such as CPU, graphic cards) implement, and enable by default TPM 2.0.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] TPM endorsement keys (EKs) are asymmetric key pairs unique to each TPM.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The TPM manufacturer usually provisions endorsement key certificates in TPM non-volatile memory.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The certificates assert that the TPM is authentic.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Starting with TPM 2.0, the certificates are in X.509 DER format.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] After the TPM was manufactured, the EKs cannot be changed.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] For fTPM, the EKs are stored on CPU / chipset when it was manufactured.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] These manufacturers typically provide their certificate authority root (and sometimes intermediate) certificates on their web sites.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] To utilize a TPM, the user needs a software library that communicates with the TPM and provides a friendlier API than the raw TPM communication.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Currently, there are several such open-source TPM 2.0 libraries.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Some of them also support TPM 1.2, but mostly TPM 1.2 chips are now deprecated and modern development is focused on TPM 2.0.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Typically, a TPM library provides an API with one-to-one mappings to TPM commands.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The TCG specification calls this layer the System API (SAPI).
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] This way, the user has more control over the TPM operations, but the complexity is high.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] To hide some of the complexity, most libraries also offer simpler ways to invoke complex TPM operations.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] The TCG specification call these two layers Enhanced System API (ESAPI) and Feature API (FAPI).
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] There is currently only one stack that follows the TCG specification.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] All the other available open-source TPM libraries use their own form of richer API.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] There is an application note about an example project for the AURIX 32-bit SoC using the tpm2-tss library.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] Requires additional libraries (dotnet) to run on Linux.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] These TPM libraries are sometimes also called TPM stacks, because they provide the interface for the developer or user to interact with the TPM.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] As seen from the table, the TPM stacks abstract the operating system and transport layer, so the user could migrate one application between platforms.
[src:remote-attestation/trusted-platform-module] For example, by using TPM stack API the user would interact the same way with a TPM, regardless if the physical chip is connected over SPI, I2C or LPC interface to the Host system.
